                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d418">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.68/289: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-29T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 29, 1940—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3780. My 3744, August 26, 2 p.m. Following the interview between the Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs and the Greek Minister the impression prevails in Greek circles
                    here that the danger of Italian action against Greece is not immediate. On the
                    basis of that impression it is not believed in those circles that the Greek
                    Government need take any emergency military measures at the moment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
